\[\tan 53^\circ \tan 81^\circ \tan x^\circ = \tan 53^\circ + \tan 81^\circ + \tan x^\circ.\]Find $x.$",46,127,True,False,parser,,"To solve the equation \(\tan 53^\circ \tan 81^\circ \tan x^\circ = \tan 53^\circ + \tan 81^\circ + \tan x^\circ\) for \(0 < x < 180\), we start by using trigonometric identities.

Firstly, recall the tangent addition formula in a special case when one of the angles is \(90^\circ - \theta\). In particular, for angles complementing each other:
\[ \tan (90^\circ - \theta) = \cot \theta \]

Define \(A = 53^\circ\) and \(B = 81^\circ\). Thus, we observe:
\[ 90^\circ - A = 37^\circ \quad \text{and} \quad 90^\circ - B = 9^\circ \]

Using the relationship \(\tan 53^\circ = \cot 37^\circ\) and \(\tan 81^\circ = \cot 9^\circ\), we rewrite the equation:
\[ \cot 37^\circ \cdot \cot 9^\circ \cdot \tan x = \cot 37^\circ + \cot 9^\circ + \tan x \]

Recognize \(\cot \alpha = \frac{1}{\tan \alpha}\), thus:
\[ \frac{1}{\tan 37^\circ \tan 9^\circ} \tan x = \cot 37^\circ + \cot 9^\circ + \tan x \]

Let \(y = \cot 37^\circ \tan x\). By plugging this in:
\[ \frac{1}{\tan 9^\circ} y = \frac{1}{\tan 37^\circ} + \frac{1}{\tan 9^\circ} + y \]
