\[ p^4 = \left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^4 = \frac{1}{625} \]

Then, we calculate \( (1-p)^{n-k} \):

\[ (1-p)^3 = \left(1 - \frac{1}{5}\right)^3 = \left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^3 = \frac{64}{125} \]

Now, we combine all these to get \( P(X = 4) \):

\[ P(X = 4) = \binom{7}{4} \cdot p^4 \cdot (1-p)^3 = 35 \cdot \frac{1}{625} \cdot \frac{64}{125} \]

We multiply the fractions:

\[ P(X = 4) = 35 \times \frac{64}{78125} = \frac{2240}{78125} \]

Finally, we put the answer in a box as requested:",1.5,Qwen/Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-Turbo,104,497,,stop,og16AfX-6Ng1vN-9efae37fea0a2c71,
